  "prompt": "How do I capture raw images from an Android camera?",
  "response": "Here's a comprehensive guide to capturing raw images on Android:\n\n1. Check Device Support\n```java\n// Check if device supports RAW capture\nCameraCharacteristics characteristics = cameraManager.getCameraCharacteristics(cameraId);\nboolean rawSupported = characteristics.get(CameraCharacteristics.REQUEST_AVAILABLE_CAPABILITIES)\n    .contains(CameraCharacteristics.REQUEST_AVAILABLE_CAPABILITIES_RAW);\n```\n\n2. Configure Camera for RAW Capture\n```java\nCaptureRequest.Builder captureBuilder = cameraDevice.createCaptureRequest(CameraDevice.TEMPLATE_STILL_CAPTURE);\ncaptureBuilder.set(CaptureRequest.CONTROL_CAPTURE_INTENT, CaptureRequest.CONTROL_CAPTURE_INTENT_RAW);\ncaptureBuilder.set(CaptureRequest.STATISTICS_LENS_SHADING_MAP_MODE, \n    CaptureRequest.STATISTICS_LENS_SHADING_MAP_MODE_ON);\n```\n\n3. Create RAW Image Capture Callback\n```java\nprivate final CameraCaptureSession.CaptureCallback captureCallback = \n    new CameraCaptureSession.CaptureCallback() {\n        @Override\n        public void onCaptureCompleted(CameraCaptureSession session, \n                                       CaptureRequest request, \n                                       TotalCaptureResult result) {\n            Image rawImage = result.getSequenceId();\n            // Process raw image\n        }\n    };\n```\n\n4. Capture RAW Image\n```java\ncameraCaptureSession.capture(captureBuilder.build(), captureCallback, backgroundHandler);\n```\n\n5. Save RAW Image (DNG Format)\n```java\nprivate void saveRawImage(Image rawImage) {\n    DngCreator dngCreator = new DngCreator(cameraCharacteristics, captureResult);\n    try (FileOutputStream output = new FileOutputStream(file)) {\n        dngCreator.writeImage(output, rawImage);\n    } catch (IOException e) {\n        e.printStackTrace();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAdditional Tips:\n- Requires Camera2 API\n- Requires Android 5.0+ (API level 21)\n- Need `CAMERA` and `WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE` permissions\n- Performance and storage intensive\n- Not all devices support RAW capture\n\nComplete Example Structure:\n```java\npublic class RawCameraCapture {\n    private CameraDevice cameraDevice;\n    private CameraCaptureSession cameraCaptureSession;\n    \n    private void setupRawCapture() {\n        // Camera setup logic\n        // Configure RAW capture parameters\n        // Create capture session\n    }\n    \n    private void captureRawImage() {\n        // Initiate RAW image capture\n    }\n}\n```\n\nLibraries/Alternatives:\n1. Camera2 API (Native Android)\n2. CameraX (Jetpack library)\n3. Third-party camera libraries\n\nPermissions (AndroidManifest.xml):\n```xml\n<uses-permission android:name=\"android.permission.CAMERA\"/>\n<uses-permission android:name=\"android.permission.WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE\"/>\n```\n\nError Handling Considerations:\n- Check device capabilities\n- Handle permission exceptions\n- Manage storage limitations\n- Consider performance overhead\n\nPerformance Optimization:\n- Use background threads\n- Implement efficient image processing\n- Manage memory carefully\n- Consider compression techniques\n\nBest Practices:\n1. Always check device compatibility\n2. Handle permissions dynamically\n3. Provide user feedback during capture\n4. Manage storage efficiently\n5. Consider image size and format\n\nDebugging Tips:\n- Use logging for capture events\n- Check camera capabilities programmatically\n- Test on multiple device configurations\n\nRecommended Workflow:\n1. Check RAW support\n2. Request permissions\n3. Configure camera\n4. Create capture session\n5. Capture image\n6. Process and save RAW data\n\nConsiderations:\n- Large file sizes (15-30 MB per image)\n- Processing overhead\n- Limited device support\n\nBy following these guidelines, you can implement robust RAW image capture on Android devices using the Camera2 API.",
